{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Both approaches involve a trade-off between diversity and quality; increased diversity typically leads to reduced quality.",
    "Empirically, we observe that the second approach (noise injection) is more effective for VAR models but results in reduced image quality.To further mitigate the reduced image quality, we propose a novel latent refinement framework called Scale-Travel.",
    "Motivated by image editing [42], inpainting [39], and reward alignment techniques [41] for diffusion models-which involve a \"time-travel\" mechanism by briefly running the generative process in reverse (i.e., the forward process in diffusion) before resuming generation-we explore an analogous mechanism for VAR based on the analogy between the denoising process in diffusion models and the scale-wise autoregressive generation in VAR.",
    "Although directly reversing the autoregressive process is infeasible, we propose leveraging the latent multi-scale autoencoder for approximate reversion.",
    "Specifically, given a partial sequence of token scales, we encode their accumulation into a full sequence of token scales, and then retain only the first few scales."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Motivated by image editing [42], inpainting [39], and reward alignment techniques [41] for diffusion models-which involve a \"time-travel\" mechanism by briefly running the generative process in reverse (i.e., the forward process in diffusion) before resuming generation-we explore an analogous mechanism for VAR based on the analogy between the denoising process in diffusion models and the scale-wise autoregressive generation in VAR."
  ]
